    {
      "id": "d210b5c03bfe8267d7ee6fe87972a6d1f74e7ec9",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2013-02-19 06:54:17.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 8: I would prefer that you didn't submit this\n\nSorry, I just don't understand why the remote MDD needs to k ow what the ROOT FID is?  Isn't it enough to do a lookup for \"ROOT\" locally, and if that fails then the ROOT is on a remote MDT and mdd_root_fid can be set to some static value that will never match any FID found locally?\n\nAlso, minor style issue in sanity.sh test_161a() - there are several in-between lines that could be converted to tabs.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 8
    },
    {
      "id": "666783c4d6e2aebb43b95562bbc5d516a9c1b655",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 147,
        "name": "Maloo",
        "email": "maloo@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "maloo",
        "tags": [
          "SERVICE_USER"
        ]
      },
      "date": "2013-02-19 08:37:30.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 8: Fails\n\nTests received by maloo, run on CentOS release 6.3/x86_64: (https://maloo.whamcloud.com/test_sessions/f1b2339a-7a6b-11e2-b916-52540035b04c).  Ran 14 tests.  1 tests failed: conf-sanity.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 8
    },
    {
      "id": "89dfbaa96119a4e7904f9d27c0349957bbe8becd",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 12,
        "name": "wangdi",
        "email": "di.wang@intel.com",
        "username": "wangdi",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2013-02-19 08:38:51.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 8:\n\nThere are several places in MDD layer, where we need check whether the FID is root, for example fid2path, is subdir check.  \n\nSpecially for fid2path, it needs to trace back to root fid, but the root fid might be fid with new sequence or IGIF,  and only MDT0 know that in current master. If the traverse happenes in MDT1,  it has no way to check and end up the path find process without knowing exact root FID.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 8
    },
    {
      "id": "e2cddf8e4bd78c626cc53ccc9518ea4ea6dfd52c",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 119,
        "name": "Alex Zhuravlev",
        "email": "bzzz@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "bzzz"
      },
      "date": "2013-02-19 08:47:31.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 8: I would prefer that you didn't submit this\n\nI'd rather agree with Andreas and not land it as is.. need to think about the problem a bit.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 8
    },
    {
      "id": "0acba0f421e325469bbaa8bcf0713249f444623f",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 119,
        "name": "Alex Zhuravlev",
        "email": "bzzz@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "bzzz"
      },
      "date": "2013-02-19 09:42:44.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 8:\n\nshouldn't we rather try to avoid lookups from one mds to another where possible?\nI guess fid2path is not prohibited for a regular user, so a lot of requests like this can arrive at time and block number of threads on MDS.\nI'd consider a model where MDT is doing traversing up till remote object is met, then return partial result to the client and let client to repeat with the correct MDS until the root is met. in turn, the client knows the root from the beginning.\nwe could also use some cache on the client to skip RPC..",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 8
    },
    {
      "id": "0a8654cd502ae2713b387db4ff809f9e5b91a8c6",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2013-02-19 16:58:59.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 8:\n\nExcuse my ignorance, but could you please detail how fid2path works for me?  I thought that MDT would return fragments of path back to client, and client will assemble it if the path crosses MDT boundaries?  It also makes sense for fid2path to take the \"root\" FID as an argument, so that processes can specify the top of the tree they are looking at, and path building will stop when the specified \"root\" FID is hit.\n\nIn either case, it doesn't seem to make sense to me that the remote MDT needs to know what the actual ROOT FID is. It can stop building the path when it hits the local proxy parent directory or any parent FID that is on a remote MDT, return the current path and parent FID to the client, and the client will call fid2path with the new parent on another MDT and repeat. The client will assemble the path fragments as needed, possibly even putting \"//\" between segments on MDTs so it is visible to the user where the MDT boundaries are.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 8
    },
